        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              PIDs are nice but not 100% necessary.  Far more important is a good grinder (I recommend the Baratza Vario) and fresh (use within 2-3 weeks!) roasted beans.<br /><br />Most of the machines &lt; $800 will be single boilers - the same boiler is used for espresso extraction and milk steaming.  As you go up in price, you get into heat-exchangers or double-boiler systems, both of which lead to better temperature stability and the ability to steam milk and extract espresso at the same time.<br /><br />My first espresso machine was a Gaggia Classic that I installed a PID on, swapped the steam wand, changed the pressure, etc.  Modded it all out.  I now have a Breville Dual Boiler and love it - two boilers, and 2 PIDs, with an actively heated group head for temp stability.  It definitely isn't as shiny as some of the Italian brands, though <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/smile.png" alt=":)" title="Smile" />.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
