        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              There are basically three &quot;levels&quot; of espresso machines: single boiler, heat exchanger, and double boiler. Under $1000, you're probably looking at a single boiler. $1000 - $2000, heat exchanger. $2000+, double boiler. These prices are approximate, I'm sure there are outliers.<br /><br />A single boiler will do fine for your first machine. They are harder to use, but you're out less money if you decide the wonderful world of espresso is not for you (it can be a LOT of work and practice until you can pull good shots). The standard go-to machines in this range are the Gaggia Classic (which I have), and the Rancilio Silvia.<br /><br />As for a PID - no, you don't need it. For the first few months (at least), you will probably be struggling with basics like grind size, bean freshness, tamp style, and dosage. Once you get the hang of all that, then you can start to contemplate adding a PID to either of these machines. A PID will help you make the temps of your shots more consistent because you won't have to &quot;temperature surf&quot; with the steam button.<br /><br />But more important than everything else - you cannot make espresso with a grinder that costs less than $200. I second the Baratza Vario. You should cheap out on the espresso machine BEFORE you cheap out on the grinder.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
