        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              I have a ~$200 Saeco, and a ~$50 burr grinder, and it makes me happy. I'm not a coffee snob though. If it's black and strong, and tastes like coffee, I'm a happy girl.<br /><br />It looks like this is the current version of what I have: <br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.amazon.com/Philips-Saeco-Espresso-Machine-Stainless/dp/B00141AZOA/ref=sr_1_2?s=home-garden&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1354553128&amp;sr=1-2&amp;keywords=saeco+espresso+makers">http://www.amazon.com/Philips-Saeco-Esp ... sso+makers</a><!-- m --><br /><br />It has a tank in the back, which I like because it means I can pull more than two shots without taking the whole thing apart (which is what you have to do for the super-cheap models). It also definitely makes nice, hot espresso, and a good head. A good head is important. <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/wink.png" alt=";)" title="Wink" /><br /><br />The snobs are right about the beans though. Starting with good beans, using a decent grinder, and figuring out the perfect amount and tamp for your machine are key. It really just depends on *how* snobby you want to be.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
