          <td class="post-date-actions">
            <div class="post-date-actions-inner">
              <div class="post-actions">
                
              </div>
              <div class="post-date">
                <a href="./viewtopic.php?p=23555478&amp;sid=ec7d24ccc47838297cead47fafade485#p23555478">Posted: Mon Dec 03, 2012 12:17 pm</a>
              </div>
              <div class="post-actions">
                
              </div>
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              A PID will help you eke the most out of the flavor profile on an espresso shot. If you go to Coffeegeek.com or the like, you'll see new blend posts often have a couple guys who go through a whole range of temps via their PIDs to determine the exact temp at which it pulls best for them. <br /><br />However, it's much like wine in that you need to train your palette to really pick up on what these guys are talking about. A non-PID Rancilio Silvia will make some excellent espresso shots when combined with a good grinder and fresh beans - and you can always hack a PID in later. <br /><br />Also, echo the recommendation on the Barazta grinders, the Vario is excellent if you want to switch around between espresso and other grinds. However, they do have the new weight based cutoff system that can either pair with their lower end grinders as an addon (the Preciso is an excellent grinder) or through the Vario-W. This allows for a consistant amount of grinds each time, and consistancy in variables is a real boon when you're trying to tweak your shots.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
